body:
I have a short test case in EDA Playground that shows a subtle behavior in Verilog when it comes to equality and values that are partially, but not fully X: https://www.edaplayground.com/x/LXvi

Copied below for convenience:

```sv
module Eq(
  input [2:0] in,
  output [2:0] out
);
  wire a = in == 3'h5;
  wire b = in == 3'h6;
  wire c = in == 3'h7;
  wire intermediate = a | b | c;
  assign out = intermediate;
endmodule

module Gt(
  input [2:0] in,
  output [2:0] out
);
  wire a = in > 3'h4;
  wire intermediate = a;
  assign out = intermediate;
endmodule

module Testbench();
  // Upper bit of in1 is set to 0, rest are X
  reg [2:0] in1;
  assign in1[2] = 0;
  wire [2:0] out1;
  Eq eq1(.in(in1), .out(out1));
  
  // All bits of in2 are X
  reg [2:0] in2;
  wire [2:0] out2;
  Eq eq2(.in(in2), .out(out2));
  
  // Upper bit of in3 is set to 0, rest are X
  reg [2:0] in3;
  assign in3[2] = 0;
  wire [2:0] out3;
  Gt gt1(.in(in3), .out(out3));

  // All bits of in4 are X
  reg [2:0] in4;
  wire [2:0] out4;
  Gt gt2(.in(in4), .out(out4));
  
  initial begin
    $display("\n\n");
    $display("in1: %h, out1: %h", in1, out1);
    $display("in2: %h, out2: %h", in2, out2);
    $display("in3: %h, out3: %h", in3, out3);
    $display("in4: %h, out4: %h", in4, out4);
    $display("\n\n");
  end
endmodule
```

This is an adapted and simplified version of something we found in SiFive's designs, as generated by the Scala FIRRTL compiler (`module Eq`) and by the CIRCT compiler (`module Gt`). CIRCT optimizes the `==` comparisons with the three constants to a `>`, since the three constants happen to be the greatest three possible values that can fit in a 3-bit value.

When you run this on VCS, it prints the following:

```
in1: X, out1: 0
in2: x, out2: X
in3: X, out3: X
in4: x, out4: X
```

According to the Verilog spec, `==` (and `!=`) is allowed to return a non-X value if enough bits of the operands are known to return an unambiguous value. In the Verilog 2005 standard, section 5.1.8 on Equality operators states:

> For the _logical equality_ and _logical inequality_ operators (== and !=), if, due to unknown or high-impedance bits in the operands, the relation is ambiguous, then the result shall be a 1-bit unknown value (x).

The rest of the section does not require an implementation to return a non-X value if you have enough information, but it seems to be carefully worded such that it allows for that behavior. In contrast, section 5.1.7 on Relational operators (<, >, <=, >=), it very explicitly states that if there is any x in either operand, then it must return a 1-bit x, thereby disallowing the optimization above.

I unfortunately don't think we can safely optimize chains of `==` operators with constant values to `>` operators, since they change the actual behavior when X's are involved.
